<HEADLINE>
Ban hopeful Mideast Quartet can help calm tensions between
Israel, Palestinians
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN 2007-05-30 19:36:53 UTC
</P>
<P>
The Quartet of Middle East peacemakers urged a halt to the recent
flare-up in fighting between Israel and Hamas militants in the
Gaza Strip, calling on the Palestinian authority to "do
everything necessary" to restore law and order.
</P>
<P>
The quartet -- Russia, the United States, the UN and the European
Union -- met Wednesday in Berlin and issued a statement urging
"all Palestinians to immediately renounce all acts of violence
and respect the ceasefire."
</P>
<P>
It called on the Palestinian authority "to do everything
necessary to resote law and order."
</P>
<P>
It condemned the firing of rockets into southern Israel from Gaza
and the buildup of arms by Hamas militants and "other terrorist
groups" in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
The four countries also called for the release of BBC journalist
Alan Johnston, who was kidnapped in Gaza on March 12.
</P>
<P>
The four Quartet diplomats -- German Foreign Minister Frank-
Walter Steinmeier, U.S. Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice,
Russian Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov and U.N. chief Ban Ki-moon
-- met at the Foreign Ministry in Berlin. The group has seen
renewed activity in recent months, though violence has continued.
They plan to meet again in June, this time with Arab
representative in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
New violence in the region has further dimmed prospects for
significant peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Israel's Security Cabinet said it would continue
its two-week-old campaign of airstrikes against cells of Hamas
militants firing rockets across the Gaza border.
</P>
<P>
Hamas' supreme leader vowed the attacks on Israel would continue.
</P>
<P>
The Quartet produced the stalled road map peace plan that was to
culminate with statehood for the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Germany, which holds the European Union and G-8 presidencies, has
been keen to restore energy to Quartet group, and it has held
several meetings this year.
</P>
